    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-15T00:13:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-15T00:13:00-05:00" n="277"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d277">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2038</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJK1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-15T14:00:00+08:47">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 15, 1918, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.14 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following delayed telegram [to Military Staff, Washington] received from
                        <persName corresp="#p_SMHH1">Slaughter</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_ECGH1">Emerson</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>May 30. Commanding officers of Czech troops at Suslovo have agreed to an
                            armistice on our arrival. Arrived Suslovo 11 a.m.</p>
                        <p>Commanders Russian forces advised us as follows: We agree to allow Czech
                            troops proceed there to carry out the original agreement, cause no
                            disturbance <hi rend="italic">en route</hi>, deliver rifles and
                            ammunition in excess twenty, officers to retain side arms.</p>
                        <p>In conference with Czech commander, Mariinsk, he stated emphatically they
                            would not give up arms and munitions. He admitted movement was concerted
                            action Czech forces in Siberia and European Russia under instructions to
                            take cities in vicinity where they were located. They would agree defer
                            action three days give us opportunity confer with their commanding
                            officer at Novo Nikolaevsk.</p>
                        <pb facs="0303" n="213" xml:id="pg_213"/>
                        <p>Russians would not allow us to [omission] our return Krasnoyarsk. Some
                            places much disturbed yesterday. Claimed French through concerted
                            movement Czech troops are trying control Siberia. President Soviet
                            Krasnoyarsk stated this morning message received from central government
                            directing Soviet to cease military operations, and that Czechs have
                            received message from their commander directing them to cease action
                            against Soviet. Soviet Krasnoyarsk states that they will bring French
                            officers from Irkutsk here by special [train], and send American mission
                            and French officers west together, in order to aid us in settling
                            remaining difficulties.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJK1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
